              <td colspan="5">
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>What is the problem under consideration? Why is government action or intervention necessary?</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><i>Substantial acceleration in the rate of annual heat pump deployment is central to decarbonising heating and achieving net zero, since heat in buildings accounts for around 22% of annual UK greenhouse gas emissions. The deployment of electric heat pumps is also an integral part of measures to support greater energy independence and reduce dependence on imported oil and gas, since more than 40% of annual UK gas consumption is for heat in buildings.</i></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><i>Along with measures such as insulation to improve the fabric efficiency of buildings, an important part of reducing energy demand is switching to more efficient heating appliances. As electric heat pumps can produce several units of heat for every unit of energy consumed, replacing a boiler with a heat pump is often the most impactful measure for reducing a building’s energy demand.</i></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><i>To enable this level of deployment, the heat pump market and supply chains need to continue to develop substantially in order to provide a wide range of attractive choices for consumers, with compelling and simple consumer journeys, supported by a wide base of skilled advisors and installers. Heat pumps are currently largely unable to compete on lifetime cost with established fossil fuel and less efficient heating options, such as natural gas and oil boilers. This is partly due to the emerging nature of low-carbon heating, which means that it does not benefit from economies of scale or from mature supply chains to the same degree as conventional technologies. Additionally, the full societal costs of fossil fuel combustion are not reflected in their market prices, including for example impacts on health and climate change. </i></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><i>In the absence of an effective policy framework, including regulatory policies such as the policy assessed here, for which powers have been granted in the Energy Act 2023, the heat pump market would not be expected to grow at the targeted rate. This would result in lower greenhouse gas emissions reductions from buildings than targeted in near-term carbon budgets. Without policies to develop the market and supply chain for heat pumps over the coming years to a sufficient capacity such as the policy assessed here, cost-effectively implementing further policy action necessary for reaching net zero emissions in the longer term may be at risk.</i></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>What are the policy objectives of the action or intervention and the intended effects?</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><i>The Clean Heat Market Mechanism (CHMM), as established by the Clean Heat Market Mechanism Regulations 2024, introduces a market obligation which establishes a platform for an industry-led transformation of the heating appliance market. As detailed in three consultations –  in October 2021, March 2023 and March 2024 – the Clean Heat Market Mechanism creates a market incentive to grow the numbers of low-carbon heating appliances installed</i></p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td colspan="5">
                <p class="ia-table-text"><i>each year, providing industry with a clear, long-term policy framework for investment and innovation. </i></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
                <p class="ia-table-text"><i>The scheme aims to:</i></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">• <i>Support the development of the UK heat pump market </i></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">• <i>Contribute to decarbonising heating in the UK and to meeting legally binding carbon budgets.</i></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
                <p class="ia-table-text"><i>This scheme sits within a wider policy framework aimed at expanding heat pump deployment and reducing greenhouse gas emissions from heating. It both complements and is complemented by other elements of that policy framework.</i></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
                <p class="ia-table-text"><i>The wider aims of government policy in this area are to:</i></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">• <i>Reduce the upfront costs of heat pumps and support households and building-owners with heat pump installations to kickstart the market;</i></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">• <i>Reduce the running costs of heat pumps, including relative to fossil fuel boilers;</i></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">• <i>Support an expansion of heat pump manufacturing in the UK;</i></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">• <i>Grow the numbers of skilled heat pump installers, and maintain high standards in the quality of heat pump installations; and</i></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">• <i>Support a range of innovations to broaden the appeal, efficiency and ease of adoption of heat pumps.</i></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><i> </i></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><i>Further detail on the government’s plans for supporting the decarbonisation of heating will be set out in due course as part of the Warm Homes Plan.</i></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
                <p class="ia-table-text"><i>A structural shift in the heating market such as this comes inevitably with high uncertainty, which is reflected in the estimates presented in this Impact Assessment.</i> </p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td colspan="5">
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>What policy options have been considered, including any alternatives to regulation? Please justify preferred option (further details in Evidence Base)</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><i>The policy options considered in this impact assessment are:</i></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">• <i>Option 0 (counterfactual): do nothing.</i> <i>In this scenario we assume there is no obligation on fossil fuel manufacturers to support deployment of low-carbon heating technologies. We assume in this scenario that heat pump deployment will be driven only by the current targeted spending and regulatory measures.</i></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
                <p class="ia-table-text">• <i>Option 1 (preferred option): introduce an obligation on the manufacturers of gas and oil boilers sold on the UK market to earn or acquire credits corresponding to qualifying installations of heat pumps in proportion to their relevant UK boiler sales. </i></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
                <p class="ia-table-text"><i>This policy is expected to continue to form part of a wider policy framework supporting heat decarbonisation; the combination of policies in this overall framework will have a bearing, for instance, on how policy costs are distributed across different groups.</i></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
                <p class="ia-table-text"><i>The principal alternatives to option 1 would be to pursue only subsidy-based measures and/or regulatory measures focused on consumers or building-owners without an accompanying market obligation. Such alternatives are less likely to reach the policy goals and would be likely to lead to higher overall social costs; they have been therefore disregarded from analysis.</i></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
                <p class="ia-table-text"><i>Option 1 has a positive Social Net Present Value (SNPV), meaning that the policy is expected to bring a net benefit to society, compared to the do-nothing scenario. Option 1 was selected as it is deemed to strike the best balance between driving heat pump uptake, achievability for businesses, and affordability.</i></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
