      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Executive Summary</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The government has an ambitious package of policy measures to help the United Kingdom enhance its energy security, become less dependent on global gas markets, and reduce greenhouse gas emissions. One important way to enhance UK energy security and accelerate decarbonisation is to reduce the energy used in buildings. In addition to measures such as insulation to improve the fabric efficiency of buildings, an important part of reducing energy demand is switching to more efficient heating appliances. Electric heat pumps have a crucial role to play in this as they can produce several units of heat for every unit of energy consumed, meaning that replacing a boiler with a heat pump is often the most impactful measure for reducing a building’s energy demand. As the UK electricity generation mix continues to reduce in carbon intensity, heating using electric heat pumps will also continue to produce fewer greenhouse gas emissions.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>As past consultations on the Clean Heat Market Mechanism set out, it is important that the heat pump market is supported to develop at pace over the coming years in order to make heat pumps a mainstream consumer solution alongside gas boilers, approximately 1.6 million of which are currently installed each year. Substantial growth in heat pump deployment, including in new-build properties, is strategically important for any energy transition pathway to net zero.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The Clean Heat Market Mechanism (CHMM) will, from 1 April 2025, place an obligation on the manufacturers of heating appliances to meet targets for the proportion of low-carbon heat pumps they sell each year, relative to fossil fuel boilers.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The Scheme Regulations, which this impact assessment accompanies, establish the target levels for the first year of the scheme; amending legislation will be required to establish any changes to the targets for years 2 to 4 of the scheme and adjust any other scheme parameters as may be necessary. If further legislation were not to be brought forward as planned, the Scheme Regulations as they are being laid would maintain the target level at the Year 1 level. Targets for Years 2-4 (and potentially beyond) will ultimately be set by the government, considering a range of factors including the feasible growth rate of the heat pump supply chain, the contribution of wider policy action to heat pump deployment, and the pace of market development necessary to meet strategic aims related to energy efficiency and emissions reductions. This impact assessment therefore assesses the impact of the Regulations being introduced, i.e. with the target set at 6% for year 1 of the scheme and without subsequent further target increases across the lifetime of the scheme.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The Regulations establish that a heat pump manufacturer will earn a credit (“a certificate”) for the installation of a qualifying domestic-scale hydronic heat pump notified via an appropriate certification scheme such as the Microgeneration Certification Scheme. To provide flexibility in how the obligation can be met, these credits are tradable. Providing further optionality in how the obligation may be met, certain installations of hybrid heat pump systems that involve both a heat pump and a fossil fuel boiler element also qualify, receiving 0.5 heat pump credits.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <content>
          <p>A range of other policies, such as the Boiler Upgrade Scheme, Social Housing Decarbonisation Fund and Energy Company Obligation, contribute to achieving the overall ambition for heat pump market growth. The Clean Heat Market Mechanism is designed to operate complementarily with this wider policy framework, with it both helping to shore up and maximise cost-effective delivery from other policies while the support to the heat pump sector from other policies helps ensure that the scheme’s targets are achievable and without disproportionate costs.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Introduction &amp; Background</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Background</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>1.</num>
        <content>
          <p>In 2008, Parliament passed the Climate Change Act 2008 (‘the Act’) which sets a legally binding goal for reducing UK greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions by 2050. The original act, passed in 2008, committed the UK to an 80% reduction of greenhouse gas emissions by 2050, compared to 1990 levels. In 2019, <a href="https://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2019/1056/contents/made"><u>the Climate Change Act 2008 (2050 Target Amendment) Order 2019</u></a> was passed which increased the UK’s commitment to reduce emissions by at least 100% below 1990 levels (i.e. Net Zero GHG emissions). </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>1.</num>
        <content>
          <p />
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>2.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The Act also requires the UK government to set ‘carbon budgets’, which are legally binding targets for UK emissions over five-year periods. The first five carbon budgets, running up to 2032, were set to achieve progress towards the previously set 80% reduction target by 2050. The Sixth Carbon Budget, set in June 2021, put into law a target to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to 965MtCO2e between 2033-2037 – meaning emissions will be approximately 77% lower (including international aviation and shipping) in 2035 than in 1990. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>3.</num>
        <content>
          <p>To meet our carbon budgets, and to reach net zero emissions by 2050, the UK must decarbonise the vast majority of heat in buildings and most industrial processes. In 2022, the buildings sector was responsible for 22% of total UK net GHG emissions. This is a critical decade for action on the decarbonisation of heat and upgrading the energy efficiency of homes and other buildings. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>4.</num>
        <content>
          <p>There are several possible pathways to full decarbonisation of heat by 2050 with a range of low-carbon technologies and systems that may have an important role to play, including a potential role for hydrogen. Heat pumps and heat networks are established technologies that will be the primary means for decarbonising heating over the next decade and play a key role in all 2050 scenarios.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>5.</num>
        <content>
          <p>As consultations on the Clean Heat Market Mechanism set out, it is important that the heat pump market is supported to develop at pace over the coming years to make heat pumps a mainstream consumer solution alongside gas boilers. If widespread use of low-carbon gas heating, e.g. hydrogen, is ruled out as a viable strategic pathway for 2050, electrified heating based predominantly on heat pumps is likely to be the most widespread solution. This would require continued market growth to over one million annual heat pump installations by the early-2030s. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Rationale for intervention</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>6.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The current market for heat pumps is relatively small: around 40,500 heat pumps were installed in pre-existing buildings in 2023<authorialNote marker="1"><p>2 MCS Installation Database. NB MCS data here may not represent the full number of heat pump retrofits in 2023, but is expected to represent the majority.</p></authorialNote>, in comparison to around 1.6 million fossil fuel boiler installations (of which ~110,000 in new-build properties).<authorialNote marker="2"><p>3BSRIA <i>UK </i><i>D</i><i>omestic Boilers</i> (2024)</p></authorialNote> Heat pumps are currently largely unable to compete on lifetime cost with established fossil fuel-based and less energy-efficient heating options, such as natural gas and oil boilers. This is partly due to the emerging nature of low-carbon heating, which means that it does not benefit from economies of scale or from mature supply chains to the same degree as conventional technologies.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>7.</num>
        <content>
          <p>A key element of the rationale for this intervention is the market failure with respect to the uncaptured negative externalities of conventional heating technologies, which renders their market price too low compared to the price of heat pumps. The full societal costs of heating based on fossil fuel combustion should consider the impacts on health (related to the air quality impacts) and the emission of greenhouse gases, leading to climate change. The need to deliver advancements in the decarbonisation of heating requires more urgent government action to correct the effects of this market failure within the UK heating system.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>8.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Likewise, the relative positive effect of heat pump deployment on air quality and emissions, and thus their lower societal cost, is not captured in their price. This is likely to result in under-investment in this technology, due to a lower expected payoff than would be provided by a market price reflecting the full range of social and private costs and benefits.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>9.</num>
        <content>
          <p>As outlined in the 2023 Clean Heat Market Mechanism consultation document, there is already a set of existing and planned policies to stimulate heat pump deployment, including heat pump subsidies (e.g. the Boiler Upgrade Scheme) and building regulations (e.g. the proposed Future Homes Standard). However, this policy framework does not provide sufficient incentive and strategic confidence to relevant market actors to develop and promote products, offerings, and services that expand the consumer appeal and therefore uptake of heat pumps in retrofit settings. Without further intervention the heat pump market is unlikely to achieve the growth needed to establish the heat pump market quickly enough to meet our decarbonisation goals.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>10.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The Clean Heat Market Mechanism (CHMM) is designed to work as part of this wider policy framework in order to provide further clarity and stimulus for investment and innovation throughout the manufacturing and installer supply chain and enable the heating industry to transform the consumer proposition of heat pumps in the UK. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>11.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Ensuring that the running costs of a heat pump are as affordable as possible is another key enabler to mass deployment. The government is keen to explore all options for making electricity cheaper and wants to ensure that consumers are supported in order to make greener choices. As such, the government is considering the most effective and efficient way to bring down the cost of electricity and the running costs of low-carbon technologies.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>12.</num>
        <intro>
          <p>Some further reasons for intervention related to the above include:</p>
        </intro>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>a)</num>
          <content>
            <p>Intervention in this market is needed to reduce the cost of decarbonising heat in buildings, as well as meeting legally-binding Carbon Budgets. Given the price effects of market failures set out above, support for the heat pump market, through a clear market growth trajectory underpinned by a market-wide obligation, is likely to improve investor certainty and generate growth and development of the supply chain.</p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>b)</num>
          <content>
            <p>Consumer research has shown that consumers are unfamiliar with heat pumps as an alternative to fossil fuel heating systems<authorialNote marker="3"><p>5DESNZ (2022), Winter public attitudes tracker, see Figure 2.1 <u>https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/1140686/BEIS_PAT_Winter_2022_Heat_and_Energy_in_the_Home.pdf</u></p><p /></authorialNote>. This lack of consumer awareness reduces their ability to choose the heating appliance based on merit, and thus constraining the technology’s ability to compete in the market. One outcome from an intervention in the market would be to raise consumer awareness, addressing this market failure.</p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>c)</num>
          <content>
            <p>Additional research and development and economies of scale are also expected to follow a successful intervention in the heat pump market. This will result in spill-over benefits to society, which are not currently reflected in the price of low-carbon heating.</p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Policy objective</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>13.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The Energy Act 2023 granted the Secretary of State the powers to introduce a market-based obligation for low-carbon heat in order to underpin an industry-led transformation of the heating appliance market. The introduction of this market obligation, the Clean Heat Market Mechanism, will create a firm market incentive to grow the numbers of heat pumps installed each year, providing industry with a clear, long-term policy framework for investment and innovation. This is expected to see the industry take a range of steps, directly and in partnership with other actors, to improve the consumer appeal and awareness of heat pumps in order to expand uptake.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>14.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Heat pump deployment at significant scale – reaching the hundreds of thousands of annual retrofit installations over the coming years – is needed to make an electrification-led pathway to net zero a viable option at least-cost. Substantial further growth in annual installations will be needed by the early 2030s.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>15.</num>
        <intro>
          <p>The main aims of the policy are:</p>
        </intro>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>1.</num>
          <content>
            <p>To support the development of the UK heat pump market to make heat pumps a mainstream consumer solution competing with gas boilers by the end of this Parliament. Working alongside other policies, the CHMM will help ensure the installation of at least 77,000 heat pumps a year in existing homes between 2024/25 and 2028/29.</p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>2.</num>
          <content>
            <p>To contribute to decarbonising heating in the UK and to meeting our legally-binding carbon budgets.</p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Outline of policy options</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>16.</num>
        <intro>
          <p>The policy options considered in this impact assessment are:</p>
        </intro>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Option 0 (counterfactual)</b>: do nothing.</p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Option 1 (preferred option)</b>: introduce an obligation on the manufacturers of gas and oil boilers sold on the UK market to hold credits corresponding to qualifying installations of heat pumps in proportion to their relevant UK boiler sales. </p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>17.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The CHMM Scheme Regulations establish the target level for the first year of the scheme; amending legislation will be required to establish any changes to the targets for years 2 to 4 of the scheme and adjust any other scheme parameters as may be necessary. If further legislation were not to be brought forward as planned, the target level would remain at the Year 1 level. Targets for Years 2-4 (and potentially beyond) will ultimately be set considering the feasible growth rate of the heat pump supply chain, the contribution of wider policy action to heat pump deployment, and the pace of market development necessary to meet strategic aims related to energy efficiency and emissions reductions. This impact assessment therefore assesses the impact of the Regulations as they are being introduced, i.e. with the target set at 6% for year 1 of the scheme and without subsequent further target increases across the lifetime of the scheme. If and when future proposals and/or legislation are brought forward to set higher targets for later scheme years, this will be accompanied by an updated Impact Assessment at that time.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>18.</num>
        <content>
          <p>We have included a qualitative assessment of the potential impact on different businesses and consumers, as well as an indicative quantitative assessment of the possible scale of direct costs to business.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>19.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The Clean Heat Market Mechanism is intended to work alongside targeted spending (e.g., the existing Boiler Upgrade Scheme) and regulatory measures (e.g., the planned Future Homes Standard) as part of an overall policy framework to support the development of the market in low-carbon heating. Future policies within this broader framework are currently at different stages of development. The principal overall policy alternative would therefore be to pursue either the same or further subsidy-based measures (e.g., heat pump grants) and/or the same or further building-owner regulatory measures alone on the demand side without an accompanying market obligation. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>20.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Meeting the heat pump deployment ambition solely through subsidy-based measures would reduce the confidence of achieving the targeted deployment outcome, relative to our preferred option; this is because the risk would remain that insufficient consumer demand and grant uptake would be seen, likely because other non-cost barriers and inertia to uptake might not have been addressed. This option would also have lower incentives, relative to the preferred option, for industry to achieve downward pressure, through competitive market efficiencies, on the overall social cost. Over time, a large subsidy regime would risk locking in inefficiencies and higher prices. Further, this approach carries the usual risks associated with setting the correct subsidy level: grants too low would not generate the demand needed to meet the deployment ambition, while grants too high would over-compensate households reducing the benefit per pound of public spend. Therefore, this alternative is less likely to reach the policy goals and would likely lead to higher overall social costs.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>21.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The same level of heat pump deployment could be achieved through regulatory measures alone, such as fossil fuel appliance installation bans for specific household segments. However, in this scenario there would be reduced incentives for an industry-led transformation of the market through competition, since the policy would provide industry with an obligated consumer base, potentially locking in expectations around current costs and prices. Further, this option would likely have significant negative distributional impacts with the targeted households forced to bear the full cost of heat decarbonisation. Therefore, this alternative is less likely to reach the policy goals and would lead to higher overall social costs or undermine the government’s goal of decarbonising the energy system in a fair and affordable way for all energy users.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>22.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Finally, a combination of grants and installation bans would help to tackle only one of the market barriers (the higher installation cost of heat pumps compared to fossil fuel alternatives) but it would not provide any incentive for the market to experiment with efforts to address the other barriers preventing consumers from installing heat pumps. Therefore, under this option, deployment might meet the necessary rates, but it could do so for a higher cost to consumers and government, compared to our preferred option.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>23.</num>
        <content>
          <p>For the reasons listed above, alternative options of meeting the deployment target without a market-based mechanism were discussed during earlier stages of analysis and further assessment was focused only on assessing the impact of different designs of the Clean Heat Market Mechanism. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <heading>Short list of options</heading>
        <paragraph>
          <content>
            <p><b>Option 0 (counterfactual): Do nothing</b></p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>24.</num>
        <content>
          <p>In this Regulatory Impact Assessment, the quantified costs and benefits of an obligation on fossil fuel boiler manufacturers (option 1) is estimated against a counterfactual where no policy is introduced (option 0). </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Option 1 (preferred option)</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>25.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The government is introducing, through secondary legislation under the primary powers granted by the Energy Act 2023, a new Clean Heat Market Mechanism (CHMM) from the financial year (FY) 2025/26, which will create a market incentive to grow the numbers of low-carbon heating appliances installed each year. This mechanism will work alongside a range of subsidy-based and regulatory policy approaches, targeted where most appropriate, to establish an overall policy framework capable of supporting a transformation of the market.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>26.</num>
        <content>
          <p>As set out in the <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/clean-heat-market-mechanism"><u>March 2023 consultation</u></a> and accompanying consultation-stage impact assessment, the CHMM will create an obligation on the manufacturers of fossil fuel heating appliances (i.e., gas and oil boilers) to achieve the sale of a certain number of heat pumps, proportional to their fossil fuel boiler sales over a given period.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>27.</num>
        <content>
          <p>In response, we would expect obligated parties to take a range of steps, both directly and in partnership with other market actors, to find and build consumer demand for heat pumps. In this way, we expect the policy to help create the conditions for rapid innovation across the market, for example, in consumer journeys and marketing, in products and product bundles, in service-based or consumer finance offerings, in the efficiency of or approach to surveys and installations, etc.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Scheme design</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>28.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The CHMM will apply throughout the UK and apply to manufacturers of fossil fuel heating appliances (i.e., gas and oil boilers) with boiler sales above a minimum threshold.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>29.</num>
        <content>
          <p>For the first year of the scheme, FY 2025/26, manufacturers of fossil fuel heating appliances will need to hold low-carbon heat pump credits corresponding to 6% of their relevant gas boiler sales in 2025/26 above 20,000 units and 6% of their relevant oil boiler sales above 1,000 units. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>30.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The scheme will continue until FY 2028/29 with a target rate of 6%. If and when future proposals and/or legislation are brought forward to set higher targets beyond year 1, this will be accompanied by a consultation and updated Impact Assessment. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>31.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Boiler sales to new-build developments and for export from the UK will be excluded. We therefore expect these targets to correspond to credits for qualifying heat pump installations totalling around 77,000 a year. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>32.</num>
        <intro>
          <p>For example, if a party sells 50,000 relevant gas boilers and 10,000 oil boilers between April 2025 and March 2026, its target for FY 2025/26 would be:</p>
        </intro>
        <subparagraph>
          <content>
            <p><subFlow name="math"><foreign><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:m="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/officeDocument/2006/math"><mml:mo>(</mml:mo><mml:mn>50,000</mml:mn><mml:mi> </mml:mi><mml:mo>–</mml:mo><mml:mi> </mml:mi><mml:mn>20,000</mml:mn><mml:mo>)</mml:mo><mml:mi> </mml:mi><mml:mi>*</mml:mi><mml:mi> </mml:mi><mml:mn>6</mml:mn><mml:mi>%</mml:mi><mml:mi> </mml:mi><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mi> </mml:mi><mml:mo>(</mml:mo><mml:mn>10,000</mml:mn><mml:mi> </mml:mi><mml:mo>–</mml:mo><mml:mi> </mml:mi><mml:mn>1,000</mml:mn><mml:mo>)</mml:mo><mml:mi> </mml:mi><mml:mi>*</mml:mi><mml:mi> </mml:mi><mml:mn>6</mml:mn><mml:mi>%</mml:mi><mml:mi> </mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mi> </mml:mi><mml:mn>2,340</mml:mn></mml:math></foreign></subFlow></p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>33.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The sale on the UK market of fossil fuel boilers fired by natural gas, liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) or oil, up to 70kWth capacity, are relevant boiler sales under the CHMM and generate a corresponding obligation. Scheme credits will be issued for the installation of ‘air-to-water’, ‘ground-to-water’ or ‘water-to-water’ heat pumps up to 45kWth. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>34.</num>
        <content>
          <p>High-temperature heat pumps will be treated the same as low-temperature heat pumps, but we will monitor market developments and consider whether any differentiation of treatment or weighting may be justified in later years of the scheme. For simplicity in this impact assessment, we have made the assumption that all installations under the obligation are low-temperature air-to-water heat pumps. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>35.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Only boiler sales for the UK retrofit market will count towards the calculation of the obligation; boilers verifiably bound for export or for new buildings are excluded. Similarly, only heat pump installations in existing UK properties will count towards the obligation. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>36.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Qualifying individual standalone heat pump installations will generate a single scheme credit for the manufacturer. Installations of qualifying hybrid heat pumps, systems that involve both a heat pump and a fossil fuel boiler element, will receive 0.5 heat pump credits. The lower weighting for hybrid heat pump installations compared with standalone heat pumps is intended to reflect: (1) the lower carbon reduction potential of these systems (given their reliance on fossil fuels); and (2) the lower energy demand reduction potential given their lower overall system efficiency, when compared to standalone heat pumps.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>37.</num>
        <content>
          <p>In order to provide flexibility in how the obligation can be met, the scheme’s credits are tradable. Obligated parties are therefore able to meet their credit obligation, in part or in whole, through acquiring credits from other heat pump manufacturers. As there are many routes to compliance, in this IA we have only modelled the impact of the heat pump deployment, regardless of the approach obligated parties decide to take to comply with the regulation. In principle, a secondary market will not affect the total number of heat pumps installed so we have assumed it to have no impact on the overall social net present value. However, an illustrative analysis of the possible distributional impact to businesses of such a secondary market is presented in the Impact on Business section.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>38.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Flexibility also comes from the fact that obligated scheme participants are able to carry forward a limited proportion of their target from one year to make up in the subsequent year, and from all manufacturers being allowed to carry forward some level of unsold or unused credits to the following year. We explore the possible impact of obligated parties carrying forward a share of their credit targets in the Risks and Uncertainties section.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>39.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Credits for the first year of the obligation will be generated with respect to heat pumps installed between 1 April 2025 and 31 March 2026, between 1 April 2026 and 31 March 2027 for the second year of the obligation, and so on.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>40.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Where obligated parties fail to meet their credit obligation, and where this shortfall exceeds the obligation that can be carried over into the subsequent year under the target carry-forward rules above, they will be required to make a payment in lieu of the remaining shortfall, at a rate of £500 per missing heat pump credit. This provides an incentive for companies to meet their targets through the sale and installation of heat pumps, or through the acquisition of heat pump credits, thereby ensuring the incentives align with the aim of the CHMM to support an expansion of the UK heat pump market. For these reasons, in the central scenario of this IA we have assumed full compliance of obligated parties. The Impact on Business section discusses the possible impact of payments-in-lieu on businesses.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Analytical approach</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>41.</num>
        <content>
          <p>This section outlines the evidence base on which impacts of the scheme have been modelled and the overall analytical approach undertaken to assess the illustrative costs and benefits of the Clean Heat Market Mechanism. The impact assessment presents the evidence of the impacts of the proposals for households, the business sector and wider society. It follows the principle of the Green Book guidance in identifying the key direct costs and benefits for these groups. The changes are compared with a counterfactual scenario and then monetised using standard Green Book appraisal values. Net present values are derived by comparing the aggregate costs and benefits which are discounted by the social discount rate.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>42.</num>
        <content>
          <p>This analytical approach has been scrutinised by the Regulatory Policy Committee (RPC) and has received a ‘Green’ rating. This is documented in the RPC Opinion Document reference: RPC-DESNZ-5055(2). The RPC’s opinion document contains summary figures based on an earlier, equivalent version of this impact assessment which used the same substantive approach and methodology. The RPC have agreed that their Green rating stands for this updated version of the impact assessment on the basis that it employs the same analytical approach to assessing the same overarching policy design. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>43.</num>
        <content>
          <p>As described above, this impact assessment reflects the legislation as it will be introduced –manufacturers of fossil fuel heating appliances will need to hold low-carbon heat pump credits corresponding to 6% of their relevant boiler sales for each year of the policy, FY 2025/26 to FY 2028/29. If future proposals and/or legislation are brought forward to adjust targets beyond the first year of the scheme, this will be accompanied by a consultation and updated Impact Assessment. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>44.</num>
        <content>
          <p>A cost-benefit approach is limited in assessing non-marginal change, such as the creation of markets and accelerated innovation, which are among the objectives of the proposal.  As such, the impact assessment is supplemented by a qualitative discussion of non-monetised costs and benefits which sets out the relevant evidence to wider strategic considerations.  Therefore, the calculated SNPVs are not intended to be viewed in isolation but should be assessed in combination with the strategic considerations. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Heat Pump Deployment assumptions</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>45.</num>
        <content>
          <p>We anticipate that under Option 1 a 6% obligation target across a boiler market of 1,600,000 sales (the approximate size of the UK boiler market in 2023<authorialNote marker="4"><p> BSRIA (2024),<b> ‘</b>Domestic boilers market analysis 2023<b>‘</b></p></authorialNote>), taking account of minimum thresholds and other exclusions in the scheme, would lead to around 77,000 heat pump installations in the first year of the obligation.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>46.</num>
        <content>
          <p>There are a wide range of UK Government schemes and policy action alongside the Clean Heat Market Mechanism which are designed to support the heat pump deployment, alongside action being taken by the Devolved Administrations. Any certified low-carbon heating retrofit installations performed in the relevant scheme year (e.g. FY 25/26) will count towards the obligation target set for that year. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>47.</num>
        <content>
          <p>We expect the Clean Heat Market Mechanism to support or enable part of this deployment, for instance through contributing to market conditions in which more building-owners take decarbonisation action in response to building regulations earlier than in a counterfactual scenario, but it is difficult to produce a quantified estimate of this contribution. For simplicity, in the counterfactual scenario of this IA we have assumed that other policies would maintain the same level of low-carbon heating appliance deployment as in the absence of the CHMM. Therefore, in the policy scenario we have estimated only the impact of the additional deployment not primarily driven by (and therefore attributed to) other policies. This has been calculated as the difference between the target and the deployment that is already assumed will take place because of other policies (the counterfactual).  </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>48.</num>
        <content>
          <p>This approach allows us to avoid any double counting of the impact of other policies. However, as we expect the market-based mechanism to be a partial enabler of the other policies, which tend to have a positive SNPV, the SNPV presented in this IA is likely to be a lower bound to the SNPV associated with the total retrofit deployment within heat pump targets.  </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>49.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The ‘Clean Heat Market Mechanism additional deployment’ depends on the deployment levels of other policies. Estimating this level of deployment is challenging and subject to a high degree of uncertainty at this stage, especially since the installation of heat pumps is only one of the possible outcomes for certain policies in consideration. In this IA we have assumed that heat pump installations driven primarily by other policies will contribute to 61,000 credits in 2025/26. With the CHMM target for 2025/26 being 77,000, this would attribute the deployment of a further 16,000 HPs to the CHMM. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>50.</num>
        <content>
          <p>In this IA, we are only accounting for CHMM additionality in 25/26 as, whilst future years’ budgets for other heat-pump-supporting schemes are yet to be finalised during the present multi-year Spending Review, we assume that they would collectively deliver significantly more deployment than the 77k CHMM target. Once the Spending Review is complete, and the Government has published further detail on its overall 'Warm Homes Plan', we will publish a further impact assessment focused on proposals for future CHMM scheme years</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>51.</num>
        <intro>
          <p>Analysis has been conducted to estimate the costs and benefits associated with low-carbon heating technologies, relative to the counterfactual. The quantified costs and benefits contributing to the SNPV are:</p>
        </intro>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>a.</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Additional upfront capital costs (Capex)</b> - These are the total additional upfront costs of the purchase and installation of low-carbon heating technologies, compared to the purchase and installation costs of the counterfactual heating system. This includes additional ancillary costs such as new radiators for heat pumps and incorporates cost reductions assumed to materialise as the market scales up.</p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>b.</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Generation costs and benefits</b> - The estimated value of the change in energy demand due to low-carbon heating technologies displacing counterfactual heating systems. This is also known as the long run variable cost (LRVC) impact. </p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>c.</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Carbon savings</b> – The estimated value of the carbon abated in both the traded and non-traded sectors due to heat from low-carbon sources replacing heat from fossil fuels.</p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>d.</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Air quality impacts</b> – The estimated value of the public health impacts of changes to emissions of nitrogen oxides and particulate matter. </p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>e.</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Maintenance</b> – The difference between the annual costs to maintain the different heating systems. For simplicity, we have assumed these costs to be the same across all scenarios and we have therefore not included them in the tables below.</p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>f.</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Hidden costs</b> – These include the time taken by householders to liaise with the installer, prepare the property for installation and any oversight. </p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>g.</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Admin and familiarisation costs </b>– The costs associated with understanding the obligation and with compliance with the scheme once in force.</p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Non-monetised costs and benefits</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>52.</num>
        <intro>
          <p>There are several non-monetised costs and benefits that are not captured in the cost-benefit analysis, including:</p>
        </intro>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>a.</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Supply chain development</b> – by incentivising additional deployment of low-carbon heat technologies relative to the counterfactual, the scheme supports the development of low-carbon heat supply chains. This will provide a basis for the mass roll-out of low-carbon heating in the 2020s and subsequent decades, which will be needed to achieve the government’s target of net zero carbon emissions by 2050. It will also help create green jobs and create opportunities for UK manufacturers. If monetised, this would have a positive impact on the SNPV.</p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>b.</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Green jobs</b> – the expansion of heat pump deployment is expected to support significant numbers of low-carbon and renewable energy (‘LCREE’) jobs. For instance the Heat Pump Association estimated that growth to 600,000 heat pump installations per year would support 30,000 LCREE jobs, predominantly in the installation and maintenance of heat pumps. This policy will contribute to securing these long-term low-carbon jobs.</p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>c.</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Innovation and cost reductions</b> – DESNZ expects that supporting low-carbon heat deployment will reduce costs and possibly increase performance over time, as supply chains develop and barriers that customers currently face are reduced through technologies being deployed successfully. The cost reduction and performance improvement benefits from low-carbon heating technologies installed after the period in scope of the market mechanism are not quantified in this impact assessment. If monetised, they would have a positive impact on the SNPV.</p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>d.</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Health benefits</b> – switching away from fossil fuels can lead to improved indoor air quality for occupants, improving their health. If monetised, this would have a positive impact on the SNPV.</p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num><b>e.</b></num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Consumer familiarity and perception towards renewable heat</b> - the DESNZ Public Attitudes Tracker indicates that 51% of the public have little to no familiarity with air source heat pumps<authorialNote marker="5"><p> DESNZ (2023), Winter public attitudes tracker - See Figure 2.1 <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/65fc5d5e65ca2f001b7da82c/DESNZ_Public_Attitudes_Tracker_Winter_2023_Heat_and_Energy_in_the_Home__Revised_.pdf"><u>https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/65fc5d5e65ca2f001b7da82c/DESNZ_Public_Attitudes_Tracker_Winter_2023_Heat_and_Energy_in_the_Home__Revised_.pdf</u></a></p></authorialNote>. However, customers who have installed renewable heating technologies have expressed high levels of satisfaction<authorialNote marker="6"><p>BEIS (2019), RHI evaluation interim report</p><p> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/rhi-evaluation-interim-report-applicant-reaction-to-reform-announcements"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/rhi-evaluation-interim-report-applicant-reaction-to-reform-announcements</u></a></p></authorialNote>. Heat pumps would require consumers and businesses to operate their heating systems in an unfamiliar way compared to conventional heating systems. The installation of hundreds of thousands low-carbon heating appliances will improve the familiarity of the public with technologies essential to reach the net zero target. If monetised, this would have a positive impact on the SNPV.</p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Modelling approach and results</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>53.</num>
        <content>
          <p>We have estimated the aggregate costs and benefits of the estimated additional clean heat installations over the years 2025/26 to 2028/29, appraised until 2045/46, when all the appliances installed are assumed to have reached the end of their lifetime. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Fuel Source Displaced</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>54.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The design of the obligation leaves the obligated parties (and their consumer base) a high degree of freedom to choose in which buildings to install low-carbon heat appliances. The mix of building-types where heating systems primarily attributable to the CHMM will be installed is therefore uncertain, but has a significant impact on the estimated carbon savings in particular. For this analysis, we have assumed that the mix of heating types being replaced with heat pumps matches that seen with the Boiler Upgrade Scheme to date<authorialNote marker="7"><p> DESNZ (2024), Boiler Upgrade Scheme’s, August statistics – See Table 1.4* <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/66f29e3b7da73f171776408d/Boiler_Upgrade_Scheme__BUS__Statistics_August_2024.xlsx"><u>https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/66f29e3b7da73f171776408d/Boiler_Upgrade_Scheme__BUS__Statistics_August_2024.xlsx</u></a></p><p>*For simplicity, we merged Oil, LPG and Coal fuel households into a combined Fossil Fuel off gas grid total and we excluded installations whose fuel type displaced is “None”, “Other” or “Unknown”. </p><p /></authorialNote>. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
