      <paragraph>
        <num>61.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The Capex value is negative as the cost of installing a heat pump is greater than that of common counterfactual technologies such as gas and oil boilers. The market-based and market-wide nature of the policy should help to keep overall costs as low as possible, with obligated parties competing to develop the heat pump market in the most efficient ways possible. A Eunomia report commissioned by DESNZ in 2022 suggests that deployment and R&amp;D could bring down the total capital cost of heat pumps, including both appliance and installations costs, by around 20% in a scenario where deployment reaches 600,000 installations per year. Therefore, we have assumed that this level of cost reduction is achieved by 2028, with a linear reduction from 2024 prices. In practice, several market participants believe that higher cost reductions can be achieved significantly faster.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>62.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Households that switch from gas boilers to heat pumps experience higher LRVC, despite the fact that heat pumps use less energy than counterfactual technologies (such as gas and oil boilers) to heat homes, due to the higher relative price of electricity. However, this is partly offset by homes, reliant on fossil fuel heating fuels, off the gas grid, where prices are more favourable to heat pumps. Overall, the LRVC impacts are a net cost. Maintenance costs are assumed to be the same in the policy scenarios and the counterfactual.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
