        <num>67.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The social benefits associated with the policy option in the central scenario more than offset the corresponding social costs, as indicated by the positive SNPV value. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Risks and Uncertainties</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>68.</num>
        <intro>
          <p>In this section, sensitivity analysis is performed against our central case, the impact of the scheme regulations. The quantified impacts laid out in the previous section are sensitive to changes in the underlying assumptions. Therefore, in this section we have tested lower and upper bounds on key input assumptions, which are discussed below. A complete list of modelling assumptions and risks is provided in the annex.</p>
        </intro>
        <subparagraph>
          <content>
            <p><b>S1: Carbon prices</b></p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>69.</num>
        <intro>
          <p>Low and high carbon value projections in the Green Book guidance are used for this sensitivity test. </p>
        </intro>
        <subparagraph>
          <content>
            <p><b>S2: Energy prices</b></p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>70.</num>
        <intro>
          <p>Low and high long run variable costs in the Green Book guidance are used to test the sensitivity on energy prices, which are expected to be highly uncertain. </p>
        </intro>
        <subparagraph>
          <content>
            <p><b>S3: Efficiency of heating system</b></p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>71.</num>
        <intro>
          <p>The efficiency of a low-carbon heating system has an impact on fuel consumption and running costs.  This is expected to vary with weather conditions, the nature of the building stock, and the level of innovation. The low and high end of the assumption range is tested here (S3). This sensitivity test is also intended to reflect uncertainty with regards to future improvements of clean heat system performance.  </p>
        </intro>
        <subparagraph>
          <content>
            <p><b>S4: Future capital cost reduction for heat pumps </b></p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>72.</num>
        <intro>
          <p>A Eunomia report commissioned by DESNZ in 2022 shows that deployment and R&amp;D could bring down the total capital cost of heat pumps, including both appliance and installations costs, by around 20% in a mass market scenario. In the central scenario we assumed this reduction to take place by 2028, with a linear reduction trajectory from 2024 prices. In the lower/upper bounds of this sensitivity analysis (S3), we explore scenarios with linear cost reduction trajectories leading to 10%/50% reductions by 2030.</p>
        </intro>
        <subparagraph>
          <content>
            <p><b>S5: Deployment assumptions – hybrid deployment</b></p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>73.</num>
        <intro>
          <p>Compared to standalone heat pumps, hybrids imply lower emissions savings as fossil fuels are used to meet part of the heat demand. The level of emissions savings for each fossil fuel hybrid installation is proportionate to the level of heat demand met by the heat pump component. In the central scenario we have assumed that 20% of the heat pumps installed in households on the gas grid are hybrids; in this sensitivity (S5), we explore the impact of a higher (50%) and lower (0%) proportion. Because of the planned credit weighting (0.5 credits for a hybrid installation vs. 1 credit for a standalone heat pump), varying the proportion of hybrid deployment has an impact on the total number of heat pumps (hybrid and standalone) deployed. </p>
        </intro>
        <subparagraph>
          <content>
            <p><b>S6: Target carry-forward</b></p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <content>
            <p>In this scenario we have assumed that obligated parties carry forward a proportion of their target from one year to the next, in line with the regulation. </p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
      </paragraph>
