      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Limitations</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>74.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Despite the sensitivity analysis conducted to flex assumptions; we are also aware of some of the limitations of the modelling. For example, we haven’t been able to consider the opportunity cost of capital due to the uncertainty on the scale of private funds used. Supplementary guidance to the Green Book on valuing energy use and greenhouse gas emissions<authorialNote marker="9"><p> BEIS (2023), Green Book supplementary guidance, <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/valuation-of-energy-use-and-greenhouse-gas-emissions-for-appraisal"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/valuation-of-energy-use-and-greenhouse-gas-emissions-for-appraisal</u></a></p><p /></authorialNote> suggests that when capital is tied up in a specific project, alternative profitable use of such capital is ruled out and there is a foregone social benefit. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>75.</num>
        <intro>
          <p>While the SNPV value presented is positive, there are the following non-monetised risks and uncertainties to consider: </p>
        </intro>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>a.</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Risk of non-compliance</b>. HMT Green Book guidance requires that central scenarios assume compliance with regulation. However, should obligated parties decide to make payment in lieu of heat pump sales, this will reduce the growth of the heat pump market and corresponding benefits. The rate of the payment in lieu has been set to mitigate this risk. This is discussed further in the impacts on business section below. </p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>b.</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Impact on cost reductions</b>. Possible supply chain constraints might decrease the ability of the policy to reduce heat pump costs over time. The government is taking steps to mitigate this risk including a £5m Heat Training Grant to support trainees in England taking training relevant to heat pumps and heat networks. This is expected to support 10,000 training opportunities up to 2025, including at least 6,000 for heat pumps. </p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Distributional impact</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>76.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The government is committed to keeping the overall policy framework for net zero under review, including how costs associated with the transition to low-carbon heating are distributed across different consumer groups. At the heart of this are efforts to help ensure that low-income and fuel-poor households are not disproportionately affected and that there is support where it is needed to make sure the transition is accessible and affordable across society.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>77.</num>
        <content>
          <p>As heat pump uptake under this scheme is on a voluntary basis, we do not expect any impact on fuel poverty. Households switching from direct electric heating to heat pumps will see a significant reduction in their energy demand because of the higher efficiency of heat pumps, with a beneficial impact on energy bills. Reducing the running costs of heat pumps, including relative to fossil fuel boilers, is an aim of wider government policy. The government is keen to ensure that consumers can make greener choices  and is considering the best and most efficient way to bring down running costs of low-carbon alternatives such as heat pumps. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Equality impact</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>78.</num>
        <intro>
          <p>Under the Public Sector Equality Duty, the government must have due regard to the potential impact of the market-based mechanism on people with protected characteristics as set out in s.149 of the Equality Act 2010 (age, disability, gender reassignment, marriage or civil partnership, pregnancy and maternity, race, religion or belief, sex, sexual orientation). This requires DESNZ to pay due regard to the need to: </p>
        </intro>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>a.</num>
          <content>
            <p>eliminate unlawful discrimination, harassment and victimisation and other conduct prohibited by the Act;</p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>b.</num>
          <content>
            <p>advance equality of opportunity between people who share a protected characteristic and those who do not;</p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>c.</num>
          <content>
            <p>foster good relations between people who share a protected characteristic and those who do not.</p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>79.</num>
        <intro>
          <p>The main groups that will be affected by the policy are:</p>
        </intro>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>a.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Households – who will decide to install the heat pumps deployed by the obligated parties</p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>b.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Installers of heat pumps – who will be contracted for installations o low carbon heat technologies</p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>c.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Manufacturers – who will need to meet the obligation.</p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>80.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Equalities Impact Assessments have been conducted throughout the scheme’s development; and a summary is provided here. Our assessment informed by stakeholder responses to both the October 2021 and March 2023 consultations – is that the implementation of the Clean Heat Market Mechanism will not disadvantage or have disproportionately negative direct impacts on any groups sharing protected characteristics. The main intended outcomes of the policy - carbon emissions reductions and strategic alignment to net zero objectives - are non-excludable public goods and therefore expected to benefit the majority of the population without distributional impacts for specific groups. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>81.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The cost of a low carbon heating system may remain a barrier to those on lower incomes, which may limit the direct benefits of the policy for this group. While lower household income is not itself a protected characteristic, it is often correlated with several protected characteristics, such as certain race and disability groups.  It is also therefore possible the policy will have higher indirect impacts for certain such groups with respect to the balance of near-term costs and benefits. However, we believe that there is strong justification for proceeding with the policy despite this potential disparity in the timing of the indirect accrual of costs and benefits to protected groups, and that it is proportionate to proceed. Without policies such as this to drive market scale and promote long-term cost reduction, costs and prices of low-carbon heating are less likely to reduce over time, meaning that the cost of switching to low-carbon heating will remain prohibitive for more households for longer.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>82.</num>
        <content>
          <p>We will continue to keep the direct and indirect impact, or potential impact, on groups with protected characteristics and on wider inequalities under review during the scheme’s implementation and during consideration of any potential changes to the scheme’s design in the future.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>83.</num>
        <content>
          <p>With respect to the second and third arms of the Equality Duty, while our assessment is that the policy will not have significant immediate impacts on either advancing equality of opportunity or fostering better relations between groups that share protected characteristics and those that do not, we believe that contributing to decreasing the cost of home decarbonisation and of energy-efficient appliances such as heat pumps through helping scale these markets and supply chains may have a minor role in reducing a current income- and/or wealth-based disparity of access to these technologies. This present disparity may disproportionately affect those in certain groups that share protected characteristics. As wider incentives start to further encourage decarbonisation, addressing this disparity, through policies such as this and others, will become increasingly important, in order to maintain equality of opportunity and preserves social cohesion and good relations between groups.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Impact on Business</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>84.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The impact of the Clean Heat Market Mechanism on businesses, both in the heating appliance sector and more broadly, will depend upon the wider policy framework for heat decarbonisation of which it is part as well as wider market developments, which will be continuing as this policy is implemented. The analysis that follows reflects our current central assumptions regarding the future costs of heat pumps and plans for other policies such as the Boiler Upgrade Scheme. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>85.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The obligation under the Clean Heat Market Mechanism applies to the manufacturers of fossil fuel heating appliances sold in the UK. The supply chain will also be affected by the obligation, as third parties might be involved in delivering the installations to meet the targets. However, in line with Better Regulation Executive guidance, these changes are defined as ‘resources used to comply with regulation’ and so their impacts are not captured in the EANDCB. A qualitative assessment of the impact on installers is included below. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>86.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Fossil fuel heating appliance manufacturing is a relatively concentrated market sector, with four companies responsible for around 91% of annual gas boiler sales (ca. 1.5m per year), and five companies responsible for around a further ~7% of sales. The four largest companies, and a number of the second-tier companies, are all multi-technology corporations producing and selling a range of appliances including heat pumps in several countries. In the oil boiler sector, four companies share around 93% of annual sales (around 55,000 per year), and another two companies a further 3%<authorialNote marker="10"><p> BSRIA (2024), ‘Domestic Boilers Market Analysis 2023’ </p></authorialNote>. The largest four also produce heat pumps. The following sections provide illustrative estimates of the main costs that these businesses might face. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>87.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Companies with boiler sales less than 20,000 relevant gas boilers and 1,000 relevant oil boilers, corresponding to roughly 1% of the UK market are exempt. Companies that meet the criteria of the small companies regime in the Companies Act 2006 are also not in scope of the obligation. These minimum thresholds and the exclusion of small companies limit the number of obligated companies and limit the costs to smaller firms or those with only limited activities in the UK. It also ensures that the administrative complexity and costs of administering the obligation are kept proportionate.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Familiarisation and admin costs</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>88.</num>
        <content>
          <p>In delivering their obligation, businesses will incur familiarisation and administrative costs. These will vary by business - depending on factors such as their setup, size and decisions on how to comply with the obligation - but are likely to include items such as the cost of running IT databases, staff time, data verification and reporting to the scheme administrator. They may also include indirect costs, such as human resources and legal costs.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>89.</num>
        <content>
          <p>We estimate familiarisation costs at the start of the scheme of around £48,000<authorialNote marker="11"><p> This is based on the illustrative assumption of 100 hours needed for familiarisation with the scheme and 13 companies in scope of the obligation. We have used the hourly wage for management consultants and business analysts (~£28/hr) from the ONS ASHE data, uplifted with the non-wage cost uplift from RPC / Eurostat 2019 (21.78%)</p></authorialNote> for the policy in total.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>90.</num>
        <content>
          <p>There are also likely to be administrative costs to these businesses associated with compliance with the scheme once in force, for instance from reporting and the provision of evidence of compliance, participation in audit processes, etc. Internal estimates, and comparisons with comparable schemes, produce an indicative high estimate of around £8m per year across all obligated parties<authorialNote marker="12"><p> Using an estimate of £0.5m admin cost per year, based on the <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/307437/impact-assessment-pir.pdf"><u>Renewable Transport Fuel Obligation post-implementation review</u></a><u>,</u>  and assuming 13 companies will be in scope with the obligation. Alternative estimates, e.g. based on other comparable schemes, are lower, so our central scenario is likely to overestimate costs.</p></authorialNote>.  As part of the monitoring and evaluation strategy below, DESNZ will commission a process evaluation which will gather evidence on these costs to inform both more accurate assessments of this policy and to contribute to assumptions for assessments of other potential policies and schemes where similar.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
