                <p class="ia-table-text">£7.1m</p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text">£6.8m</p>
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Obligation costs</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>91.</num>
        <intro>
          <p>The cost to businesses of meeting their CHMM obligations are difficult to assess with confidence. At the lower end of the range, they could amount only to the familiarisation and administrative costs estimated in the section above. However, the difference in cost between heat pump and fossil fuel systems and the presence of market barriers and failures means that there are scenarios where businesses may need to subsidise heat pumps to induce households to install them. For each installation, the size of such subsidy required would be affected by several factors:</p>
        </intro>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>a.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The speed at which heat pump costs fall relative to fossil fuel systems as the market develops. </p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>b.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Consumer familiarity and willingness to pay a premium for heat pump installations (over boiler replacements) and how these changes over time. </p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>c.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The extent to which other policies supporting the deployment of heat pumps reduce costs. This could be directly with subsidy such as the Boiler Upgrade Scheme and Warm Homes Social Housing Decarbonisation Fund. Other policies, including financial support for training and/or manufacturing will also lower costs to businesses.</p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>d.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The difference in annual running costs for customers between heat pumps and fossil fuel systems. This is determined by retail energy prices and associated policy. </p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>e.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The development of the market for installation credits and the extent to which businesses wish to use these to meet their obligations. </p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>f.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The extent to which higher revenues from heat pump sales and increased market share are of value to businesses. </p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>92.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The possibility to trade credits means that the costs faced by different obligated parties could vary significantly, depending on whether they decide to meet their credit obligation, in part or in whole, through acquiring credits from other heat pump manufacturers. Some of the costs that obligated parties will face are transfers between businesses; others will be offset by direct benefits to business. In line with Better Regulation Executive guidance, we have excluded these costs from the total. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>93.</num>
        <content>
          <p>In the least-cost scenario for obligated parties, heat pumps would either be cost-equivalent with fossil fuel technologies, or a combination of consumers' willingness to pay and/or policy subsidy would be sufficient to cover the difference in cost.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>94.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Obligated parties have the option to make a ‘payment in lieu’ instead of selling a heat pump at a cost of £500. If the costs of subsidising heat pumps to achieve the necessary sales is too high, they may prefer to make these payments. We can therefore consider the maximum cost to business as the total number of heat pump sales attributed to the CHMM multiplied by this £500 payment amount, plus the familiarisation and admin costs described above. These costs are estimated in table 12 below. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>95.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Should boiler manufacturing businesses decide to meet the obligation by selling heat pumps themselves, they may need to subsidise these heat pumps to encourage households to install them. This subsidy (delivery cost), if present, would be a direct cost to business. We estimate that this cost to business is between our minimum and maximum estimates described above. All the additional costs associated with manufacturing, marketing and installing the heat pumps over and above the equivalents for boilers should be considered direct costs associated with the scheme; however, they will be (fully or partly) offset by the direct revenues generated from the heat pump sales. This means that the only true cost to business would be the possible extra subsidy they might need to offer to persuade some households to install heat pumps.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>96.</num>
        <content>
          <p> The development of the market could significantly reduce these delivery costs, for example, if consumers were presented with affordable options for multi-year financing, this might increase their demand for and willingness and ability to pay towards heat pump installations. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>97.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Within our analysis there is an assumption that consumers’ willingess to contribute towards the cost of their heat pump installation will reduce the cost for obligated parties by £2500 per installation on average. This is an illustrative estimate and is based in part on evidence from the Boiler Upgrade Scheme to date, which suggests that applicants are willing to contribute, on average, around £8000 for the total cost of the heat pump (and therefore over £5000 on top of the cost of an average boiler). However, these applicants to the scheme to date may be considered early adopters with a particular interest in decarbonisation. In future years, one might expect the average willingness to pay to decrease as deployment increases; on the other hand, as the market develops, it is likely there will be increased consumer awareness as well as new financing arrangements that could combine to make it easier to find a greater number of willing-and-able-to-pay heat pump consumers.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>98.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Consumer demand, as well as all the other factors affecting the subsidy cost listed above, must be considered when setting the level of the payment in lieu. The level of the payment in lieu will be kept under review throughout the lifetime of the policy, to ensure that it provides an incentive for obligated parties to sell heat pumps and/or purchase equivalent credits. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
