      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Evaluation</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>121.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Arrangements for the evaluation of the CHMM are currently subject to a decision as to whether it will receive its own policy level evaluation or be evaluated as part of a wider evaluation of the EoH Programme in which it sits.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>122.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The benefits of a programme evaluation are that it is better placed to assess shared impacts where individual policy evaluations struggle to attribute impact to a particular scheme in a busy policy environment where multiple mechanisms are attempting to stimulate the same results. However, this comes at the expense of a greater volume of policy specific evidence, particularly in the process evaluation, which is better served by individual policy evaluations.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>123.</num>
        <content>
          <p>In this absence of this decision, this section will provide assurances that all relevant considerations are being taken into account in designing an appropriate evaluation and provide some insight into what either evaluation approach could look like. It also seeks to assure readers that at least a minimum of evaluation activity will be undertaken to assess the CHMM or the EoH Programme in which it resides, against their respective objectives.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Approach &amp; Methodology</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>124.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Any design would see the evaluation providing an assessment of whether the CHMM realised it’s intended impacts (benefits and wider impacts), drawing on secondary monitoring data and primary data collection, to support the aims of its impact evaluation component. The impact evaluation is likely to employ quasi-experimental impact analysis, which will be scoped in partnership with existing academic experts. This may be supplemented by theory-based approaches, such as contribution analysis, where particular impacts do not lend themselves to quasi-experimental approaches.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>125.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Whether realised impacts constituted value-for-money will also be part of the evaluation. Social cost-benefit analysis synthesised alongside wider evaluation evidence in a 3E’s approach is likely to be the preferred method of economic evaluation. An existing economics consultant will support the design of this work.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>126.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Scheme processes or wider programme delivery for a policy or programme evaluation respectively, and the extent to which barriers and enablers in these respects facilitated the realisation of impacts, will be the subject of a process evaluation.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>127.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Any evaluation design will inevitably provide various avenues for primary data collection, using qualitative methods and/or surveys. Though these will principally provide data to support an assessment of the extent to which the CHMM met its objectives, there will also be an opportunity to pursue wider areas of inquiry relevant to the CHMM and Clean Heat policy more broadly.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Evaluation delivery, outputs and timelines</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>128.</num>
        <content>
          <p>It is most likely that this evaluation will adopt a hybrid delivery approach, whereby responsibility for undertaking the evaluation is split between DESNZ analysts and external evaluation suppliers. This approach would see external evaluation suppliers collecting primary data, leading on the majority of analysis and producing outputs, to ensure the impartiality of this work. The supplier will be recruited through a fair and open competition and will be assessed based on price and the quality of their bid for this project. However, where the skills of internal DESNZ analysis can be utilised, such as in undertaking basic statistical analysis of monitoring data or producing cost-benefit analysis, they will undertake this work, subject to oversight from the supplier, to ensure value-for-money.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>129.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The supplier will produce a range of outputs, which may take the form of reports, dashboards and data tables, containing the findings of the evaluation.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>130.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The findings from any evaluation will be synthesised annually and contained in a published annual interim report. A final synthesis report will be published at the end of the evaluation.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>131.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Findings from the evaluation will be used to support the design and implementation of any future scheme which seeks to support the uptake of low carbon heating and will generate transferable knowledge which is also relevant in respect of other energy efficiency measures, and/or market-based policy interventions in other sectors. The evaluation will also seek to explore the emergence of any perverse incentives or unforeseen impacts of the CHMM.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>132.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Any evaluation will run from 2025 to 2029. In the case of a CHMM policy evaluation, this will ensure that any future years of the scheme post-2025 are subject to an evaluation, whereas for a programme evaluation, this means it will conclude at a point when the constituent policies in the programme are all ending.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>133.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Appropriate budget and resources are being sought within DESNZ to deliver the evaluation.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
